'''Classicide''' is the deliberate and systematic destruction, in whole or in part, of a [[social class]] through persecution and violence.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /> The term "classicide" was termed by sociologist [[Michael Mann (sociologist)|Michael Mann]] as a term that is similar but distinct from the term [[genocide]]. Examples includes [[Mass killings in the Soviet Union|Joseph Stalin's mass killing]] of the affluent middle-class peasant [[Kulaks]] who were identified as "class enemies" by the [[Soviet Union]]. Similar classicide has been committed by [[China]] during the [[Great Leap Forward]], by [[North Vietnam]] as part of the [[Land reform in North Vietnam|Land Reform]], and by the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime in [[Cambodia]].
== Definition == Classicide is a term first used by Frederick Schwarz in his book ''The Three Faces of Revolution''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Three Faces of Revolution|last=Schwarz|first=Frederick|publisher=Capital Hill Press|year=1972|isbn=978-0882210032|pages=51–53}}</ref> It was used later by [[Michael Mann (sociologist)|Micheal Mann]] as a well defined term. Classicide has since been used by [[Michael Mann (sociologist)|sociologists]]<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/soc/faculty/mann/theses.pdf|title=Explaining Murderous Ethnic Cleansing: Eight Theses|last=Mann|first=Michael|date=Spring 2002|website=[[UCLA]]|format=PDF|publication-place=Brisbane, Australia|access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title=What is Genocide?|last=Shaw|first=Martin|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2015|isbn=978-0745631837|pages=72}}</ref> to describe the unique forms of [[genocide]] that pertains to the annihilation of a class through murder or displacement. Commonly used to describe the [[The Communist Manifesto|ideals]] of [[Karl Marx]]<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/download/pdf/Manifesto.pdf|title=The Communist Manifesto|last=Marx|first=Karl|publisher=Progress Publishers|year=1848|location=London, England|pages=22–27}}</ref> and the destruction of the [[Bourgeoisie|upper class]] to form an equal [[Proletariat|working class]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" />
== History ==
=== USSR === {{main article|Dekulakization}} ==== Classicide of Kulaks ==== In 1929, at the beginning of his dictatorship, [[Joseph Stalin]] demanded the "liquidation of kulak's as a class".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Harvest of Sorrow: Soviet Collectivization and the Terror-Famine|last=Conquest|first=Robert|publisher=Oxford Press Inc.|year=1986|isbn=0-19-504054-6|location=198 Madison Avenue, New York, New York, 10016-4314|pages=}}</ref> The [[Kulak]]<nowiki/>s were peasants who were deemed "wealthy" by Stalin in 1929. The idea for [[dekulakization]] first arose in 1918 from [[Vladimir Lenin|Vladamir Lenin]], who claimed that the Kulak's were "freeloaders".<ref>А.Арутюнов «Досье Ленина без ретуши. Документы. Факты. Свидетельства.», Москва: Вече, 1999</ref> The oppression of kulaks didn't end until 1932, throughout this time Kulak's were being evicted from their homes, having their land confiscated, shot, imprisoned, deported, or being sent to local work camps.<ref name=":0" /> Although the term classicide was never formally used to describe Stalin's destruction of the kulaks, Stalin did say that they had "... gone over from a policy of limiting the exploiting tendencies of the kulak to a policy of eliminating the kulaks as a class."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcriterion.com|title=Stalin's ism|last=Kotkin|first=Steven|date=6 February 2018|website=New Criterion|archive-url=https://www.newcriterion.com/issues/2017/11/stalins-ism|archive-date=November 2017|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> During the punishment of the kulaks under Stalin's leadership an estimated 14.5 million peasants died from starvation or punishment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=|last=Methvin|first=Eugene|date=11 December 1995|work=[[National Review]]|issue=23|volume=47}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=February 2018|reason=There's no article by Methvin in the 11 December 1995 issue. But there is a "Hitler & Stalin: Twentieth-Century Superkillers" cover story by him in the May 31, 1985 issue. There are also stories in other issues in 1995 that may be what's intended.}}
===China=== {{main article|Mass killings of landlords under Mao Zedong}} In 1947, during the [[Chinese Civil War]], three years before the [[People's Republic of China]], [[Mao Zedong]] won the hearts of the [[Communist party|Communist Party]] and the peasant class by introducing a new land reform. This land reform encouraged the mass murder of [[landlord]]s and well-off peasants in order to redistribute the land to the peasant class and other landless workers. The idea of killing landlords was first outlined by Kang Sheng, expert in terror tactics, in 1947. Ren Bishi, a member of the communist party's central committee, stated that "30,000,000 landlords and rich peasants had to be destroyed" (Rudolph J).<ref name="www.theepochtimes.com">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/how-mao-radicalized-peasants-to-kill-landlords_2232983.html|title=How Mao Radicalized Peasants to Kill Landlords|date=2017-03-15|work=www.theepochtimes.com|access-date=2018-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref> The reform was an open door for violence when Mao insisted that the peasants themselves should do the killing. Landlords were tortured. They were dismembered, buried alive, strangled, shot, etc. There is no way to know exactly how many people were killed but the numbers range anywhere from one million to 28 million.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
=== Cambodia === {{main|Cambodian genocide}} In 1969 in the midst of the [[Vietnam war]],<ref name=":4">{{Cite book|title=Under Attack: genocidal ideology and the homeland at war|last=Murray|first=Elisabeth Hope|publisher=the university of Edinburgh|year=2011|isbn=1 900522 98 5|location=the university of Edinburgh|pages=36}}</ref> [[President Nixon]]<ref name=":5">{{Cite book|title=under attack: genocidal ideology and the homeland at war|last=Murray|first=Elisabeth hope|publisher=the university of Edinburgh|year=2011|isbn=1 900522 98 5|location=the university of Edinburgh|pages=36}}</ref> staged massive attacks on [[Cambodia]]n soil due to his beliefs that there were communist base camps as well as supplies and infantry hidden in Cambodia by the [[Viet Cong]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite book|title=under attack: genocidal ideology and the homeland war|last=Murray|first=Elisabeth hope|publisher=the university of Edinburgh|year=2011|isbn=1 900522 98 5|location=the university of Edinburgh|pages=36}}</ref> Nixon also believed the Viet Cong enemy was bombing US soldiers from bases established in Cambodia as well. Cambodia’s then-president [[Lon Nol]]<ref name=":5" /> was initially unaware and did not address any of the Nixon bombings so they lasted from 1969-1975.
Victims of the US attacks saw the American enemy as rich, upper-class and viewed Lon Nol as possessed the same characteristics as Nixon—rich and powerful. [[Pol Pot]]<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppu.org.uk/genocide/g_cambodia1.html|title=GENOCIDE - CAMBODIA|website=www.ppu.org.uk|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref> recognized the fear and hatred the people of Cambodia had towards the upper class and used this hostile environment as a tactic to gain control over the lower and upper classes which brought the [[Khmer Rouge]] reign his control.
To enforce his control over the regime, he would need to cleanse the country of anyone who fit the description of 'upper class’, and also the ‘Khmer minority’<ref name=":4" /> who shared cultures with the former leader, Nol. Supporters of Nol were primarily rich, upper-class elite. Therefore, Pol Pot targeted these individuals. Anyone who was educated including doctors, lawyers, and teachers were murdered.<ref name=":7" /> Following the bombings, by Americans, Pol Pot persuaded victims of the bombings to join the Khmer Rouge by playing on their fearful state of mind. Anyone who would not cooperate was simply murdered.
Pol Pot’s actions eventually led to displacement and created refugees. He soon abolished civil and political liberties<ref name=":7" /> which allowed his policies for genocide to be permissible and remained unchecked. Although the majority of the Khmer population massacred were mostly Vietnamese immigrants and [[Cham minority]],<ref name=":4" /> over 2 million Khmer natives were still murdered.<ref name=":7" /> Children were ripped from their families and their parents were killed in cold blood, soldiers and foreign language speakers were not excluded in the killings either. Pol Pot continued his raids by attacking border towns of Vietnam, which eventually ended his reign. Many natives of Cambodia believed that if it weren’t for the Vietnamese army fighting back, the killings would have lasted longer.<ref name=":6" />
=== North Vietnam === {{main article|Land reform in North Vietnam}} [[Ho Chi Minh]], the former leader of North Vietnam, instituted [[Land reform in North Vietnam|land reform]] in the 1950s to redistribute land from the holdings of landlords to the peasantry.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lind|first1=Michael|title=Vietnam: The Necessary War|date=2013|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781439135266|pages=151–155|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqCCznBqpdcC&pg=PA151&dq=%22vietnam%22+%22class+genocide%22+%22land+reform%22+-site:.com&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwii2qfHk4TZAhUV22MKHTuBAIYQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22vietnam%22%20%22class%20genocide%22%20%22land%20reform%22%20-site%3A.com&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The landlords in North Vietnam became targets of smear campaigns by the government, in hopes that the peasantry would revolt against the upper class. Stories of rape, murder, and exploitation of the peasantry by landlords were told to gain the lower classes's support.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tucker|first1=Spencer C.|title=The Encyclopedia of the Vietnam War: A Political, Social, and Military History, 2nd Edition [4 volumes]: A Political, Social, and Military History|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851099610|pages=621|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qh5lffww-KsC&pg=PA621&dq=%22vietnam%22+%22land+reform%22+-site:.com&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbtMiJ54fZAhUPyGMKHaEUB-EQ6AEIOjAD#v=onepage&q=%22vietnam%22%20%22land%20reform%22%20-site%3A.com&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The government purged landlords as a class. They were executed by firing squads, stoning, and starvation with some being put into reeducation programs.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Malarney|first1=Shaun Kingsley|title=Culture, Ritual and Revolution in Vietnam|date=2002|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=9780824826604|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kwdh3n6cdokC&pg=PA23&dq=%22vietnam%22+%22land+reform%22+-site:.com&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbtMiJ54fZAhUPyGMKHaEUB-EQ6AEIVTAI#v=onepage&q=%22vietnam%22%20%22land%20reform%22%20-site%3A.com&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The number of landlords killed during the years of the land reform, range from 5,000 to 50,000.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_y99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&dq=%22vietnam%22+%22land+reform%22+-site:.com&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixqqK-9I3ZAhVK4GMKHfssBcAQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=%22vietnam%22%20%22land%20reform%22%20-site:.com&f=false|title=Soviet-Vietnam Relations and the Role of China 1949-64: Changing Alliances|last=Olsen|first=Mari|date=2007-05-07|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781134174126|location=Routledge, 2007|pages=|language=en}}</ref> While the term classicide hasn't been used to distinguish the event, the term "class genocide" appears in [[Michael Lind|Micheal Lind]]'s book, ''Vietnam: The Necessary War''.
== Elimination of lower classes ==
=== El Salvador === {{main article|1932 Salvadoran peasant massacre}} Maximiliano Hernandez Martinez crushed an uprising of the [[peasant]] class with wholesale massacre of 10,000 to 40,000 civilians.<ref>University of California, San Diego (2001) "El Salvador elections and events 1902-1932</ref> === Anti-homelessness laws === {{further|Homelessness in the United States#Criminalization of homelessness}} {{further|Anti-homelessness legislation}}
Anti-homeless laws can criminalize homelessness and begging.<ref>[[Anti-homelessness legislation#Laws criminalizing behaviors engaged in by the homeless]]</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=March 2018}} Measures that prohibit natural human survival needs is referred to as anti-homeless laws.<ref name="nationalhomeless">“Criminalization.” National Coalition for the Homeless, nationalhomeless.org/issues/civil-rights/.</ref> “Critics of homeless criminalization claim that such measures do nothing to actually solve homelessness and in fact make matters worse. Homeless people find it harder to secure employment, housing, or federal benefits with a criminal record, and therefore penalizing the act of being homeless makes exiting such a situation much more difficult.”<ref>[[Homelessness in the United States#Criminalization of homelessness]]</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=March 2018}} Court rulings on anti-homeless laws can either challenge or reinforce the laws and can lead to exclusion of the homeless from society.<ref>Kathryn Hansel, Constitutional Othering: Citizenship and the Insufficiency of Negative Rights-Based Challenges to Anti-Homeless Systems, 6 Nw. J. L. & Soc. Pol'y. 445 (2011). https://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/njlsp/vol6/iss2/11</ref> “Unfortunately, over the past 25 years, cities across the country have penalized people who are forced to carryout out life-sustaining activities on the street and in public spaces; despite the fact these communities lack adequate affordable housing and shelter space. Ultimately, many of these measures are designed to move homeless persons out of sight, and at times out of a given city.”<ref name="nationalhomeless" />
